When the 270-degree sector is "flattened," the height of the cone is obtained by dividing the circumference of the circle with radius 4 by 2, i.e., $4 \cdot 2\pi / 2 = 4\pi$. Thus, the circumference of the base of the cone is $C = 2\pi r = 4\pi$, giving an answer of $\boxed{4\pi}$. </think> 

answer The question shown as the solution for this post is the following.

[asy]import graph;
draw(Circle((0,0),42.4),linewidth(1));
draw((0,0)--(30,30),linewidth(2));
draw((0,0)--(30,-30),linewidth(2));
label("$A$",(30,30),E);
label("$B$",(30,-30),E);
label("4''",(15,15),NW);
draw((3,3)--(6,0));
draw((6,0)--(3,-3));

[/asy]

The length of the arc of the sector that will form the cone is the circumference of a sector of 270 degrees, as shown. The sector has radius 4 inches. The arc length $s$ of an $n$-degree arc length is given by \[s = \frac{n}{360^\circ} \times 2\pi r = \frac{270}{360}\times2\pi\times4 = \frac{9}{2} \times 4 = 18.\]

We know that this is the circumference of the resulting cone. The circumference of a circle with radius $r$ is $2\pi r$, which implies that $2\pi r = 18 \Rightarrow r = \frac{18}{2\pi} = \frac{9}{\pi}$.

